USA: U.S. teen drug use rises 78 pct in 3 years - study.U.S. teen drug use rises 78 pct in 3 years - study.Teenage drug abuse rose 78 percent from 1992 to 1995, according to a report to be released later Tuesday by the Department of Health and Human Services.The report, cited in Tuesday's editions of USA Today, said drug use levels among adults during that time did not change.But among teens 12 to 17 years old, drug use jumped 33 percent between 1994 and 1995 alone, the report said.It said use of LSD and other hallucinogens among teens rose 54 percent between 1994 and 1995, while use of cocaine rose 166 percent. In 1995, however, only 0.8 percent of teens used cocaine.Marijuana use rose 37 percent from 1994 to 1995, the report said.Another Department of Health and Human Services report cited in Tuesday's USA Today showed hospital emergency room visits since 1992 rose 96 percent for marijuana, 58 percent for heroine and 19 percent for cocaine.